00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:27.020
MARK HARVEY: We have Neil
Leonard with us again.

00:00:27.020 --> 00:00:30.100
You all heard the great
concert we had on Wednesday.

00:00:30.100 --> 00:00:31.610
So we thought we'd
start out just

00:00:31.610 --> 00:00:37.020
by asking if anybody had any
questions or comments based

00:00:37.020 --> 00:00:41.202
or that, that you'd like to ask
the performer while he's here.

00:00:41.202 --> 00:00:44.652
AUDIENCE: Did it go how
you expected it to go?

00:00:44.652 --> 00:00:46.610
NEIL LEONARD: I was
pleased with how it worked.

00:00:46.610 --> 00:00:53.340
I didn't really-- I
wasn't really sure

00:00:53.340 --> 00:00:55.730
how it would all go.

00:00:55.730 --> 00:00:59.970
I kind of had the
basic idea, but there

00:00:59.970 --> 00:01:03.210
was a lot of logistical
stuff to do leading up to it.

00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:06.450
I was finishing a piece of
the final piece we pay played.

00:01:06.450 --> 00:01:08.610
I'd finished that
week, so I just

00:01:08.610 --> 00:01:15.270
had my mind full of
details to take care of.

00:01:15.270 --> 00:01:18.620
But I was really
pleased at how it went.

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:25.505
And I also was really pleased
because Robin, my collaborator,

00:01:25.505 --> 00:01:28.430
was very enthusiastic and
wanted to do it again.

00:01:28.430 --> 00:01:30.510
And so, that's kind
of like a goal.

00:01:30.510 --> 00:01:33.960
If I do something with
a group of musicians,

00:01:33.960 --> 00:01:38.860
to reach the point where people
would want to do it again.

00:01:47.410 --> 00:01:47.980
Anybody else?

00:01:47.980 --> 00:01:49.170
I think last week I
threatened to make

00:01:49.170 --> 00:01:50.211
everybody ask a question.

00:01:55.630 --> 00:01:58.200
AUDIENCE: Usually I feel
like a lot of the technology

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:01.612
that people use detracts
from the performance,

00:02:01.612 --> 00:02:05.580
but I felt like, definitely,
in this performance

00:02:05.580 --> 00:02:10.509
it added a lot of value to
what the audience was hearing.

00:02:10.509 --> 00:02:11.630
NEIL LEONARD: How so?

00:02:11.630 --> 00:02:17.040
AUDIENCE: It allows
one person to create

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:20.770
so much variety of
sound, and the audience

00:02:20.770 --> 00:02:26.171
was able to here all of
the sound at the same time.

00:02:26.171 --> 00:02:29.105
When you're just
playing by yourself,

00:02:29.105 --> 00:02:33.727
there's only so much you can do.

00:02:33.727 --> 00:02:35.102
NEIL LEONARD: I
guess, especially

00:02:35.102 --> 00:02:36.660
if you're playing
a wind instrument.

00:02:36.660 --> 00:02:43.580
I was reading a biography
of this really famous sax

00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:45.450
player, Stan Getz.

00:02:45.450 --> 00:02:51.620
And he did a recording in,
I'm guessing in the '70s,

00:02:51.620 --> 00:02:54.720
with like a echo kind of box.

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:56.420
Things a tape delay.

00:02:56.420 --> 00:02:58.080
An analog tape delay.

00:02:58.080 --> 00:03:00.725
And he talked about--
the first recording

00:03:00.725 --> 00:03:02.980
he made was published,
it sounds wonderful--.

00:03:02.980 --> 00:03:04.385
Have you ever heard that, Mark?

00:03:04.385 --> 00:03:04.650
MARK HARVEY: Who's the Guy?

00:03:04.650 --> 00:03:04.878
NEIL LEONARD: Stan Getz.

00:03:04.878 --> 00:03:05.030
Playing through the echo.

00:03:05.030 --> 00:03:06.290
MARK HARVEY: Yes, I have.

00:03:06.290 --> 00:03:09.030
NEIL LEONARD: It's
called "Another World,"

00:03:09.030 --> 00:03:10.680
or something like that.

00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:12.590
He plays wonderfully,
but he also

00:03:12.590 --> 00:03:16.980
says that this is a time when,
in the jazz world-- and I think

00:03:16.980 --> 00:03:21.450
that in so-called rock
music, electronics

00:03:21.450 --> 00:03:23.610
were embraced,
and don't really I

00:03:23.610 --> 00:03:25.870
don't remember them
being challenged.

00:03:25.870 --> 00:03:30.850
If Pink Floyd , or Jimi Hendrix,
or somebody had synthesizers,

00:03:30.850 --> 00:03:33.510
that just seemed like it was OK.

00:03:33.510 --> 00:03:39.010
For jazz musicians, it
seemed like it was somehow

00:03:39.010 --> 00:03:41.290
straying from this
tradition that

00:03:41.290 --> 00:03:43.120
shouldn't be tampered with.

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:47.980
And Stan Getz said that
it felt natural to him.

00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:52.330
And it gave him
something to do, which

00:03:52.330 --> 00:03:52.860
you couldn't do with the sax.

00:03:52.860 --> 00:03:54.060
You play harmony.

00:03:54.060 --> 00:03:56.916
So if he played a delay,
he could play one note,

00:03:56.916 --> 00:03:59.290
and while that note's ringing,
he could play second note,

00:03:59.290 --> 00:04:01.140
and make chords, basically.

00:04:01.140 --> 00:04:05.930
Which he'd never been
able to do before.

00:04:05.930 --> 00:04:10.210
There's also another
instance from around that era

00:04:10.210 --> 00:04:11.310
that caught my attention.

00:04:11.310 --> 00:04:17.390
There was a flute
player named Paul Horn.

00:04:17.390 --> 00:04:19.640
And he did a recording
at the Taj Mahal.

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:21.640
And I think it was like
this gorilla recording

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:24.557
where he walked in and
set up his tape deck.

00:04:24.557 --> 00:04:27.140
Now you probably couldn't take
a tape deck into the Taj Mahal.

00:04:27.140 --> 00:04:28.240
I'm guessing.

00:04:28.240 --> 00:04:29.500
Or into the Vatican.

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:31.847
You'd be screened.

00:04:31.847 --> 00:04:34.430
But he said he pulled the tape
deck out and started to record,

00:04:34.430 --> 00:04:35.513
and it was the same thing.

00:04:35.513 --> 00:04:37.400
It is a very, very
long reverberation,

00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:42.060
so you can build
harmonic structures

00:04:42.060 --> 00:04:46.260
for the flute, which you
can't do in a room like this

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:48.070
without the use of electronics.

00:04:48.070 --> 00:04:55.600
And so, I don't see a
difference between using the Taj

00:04:55.600 --> 00:04:59.800
Mahal to do that, versus
using, like, analog tape delay.

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:02.960
If you get to play chords,
and that's a really fun thing

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:06.642
to play with, then I want to
experiment playing chords.

00:05:06.642 --> 00:05:08.600
If I can get the Taj
Mahal, I'm happy to get it

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:11.200
but, I'm not going to bring
the Taj Majal to Killian Hall

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:12.664
downstairs.

00:05:12.664 --> 00:05:14.080
Whatever I bring
is probably going

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:17.830
to be some kind of
computer software.

00:05:17.830 --> 00:05:19.540
But in principle--

00:05:19.540 --> 00:05:21.370
AUDIENCE: I wasn't
saying like-- I just

00:05:21.370 --> 00:05:25.294
feel that usually things
don't work as expected.

00:05:28.350 --> 00:05:32.032
People will bring in things, and
mics won't work, or whatever.

00:05:32.032 --> 00:05:34.669
At the end of the
performance, it

00:05:34.669 --> 00:05:36.585
might have been better
if they just played it.

00:05:36.585 --> 00:05:40.214
But in this case, things worked
out the way you wanted them to.

00:05:44.054 --> 00:05:45.970
NEIL LEONARD: Not
everything worked perfectly.

00:05:45.970 --> 00:05:54.220
And I was interested in when
things didn't work perfectly.

00:05:54.220 --> 00:05:57.320
It was still a performance,
and if something doesn't work,

00:05:57.320 --> 00:05:59.129
you go ahead.

00:05:59.129 --> 00:06:00.920
At one point, I put
the wrong page of music

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:04.260
in the music stand, so
when we got to that point,

00:06:04.260 --> 00:06:05.620
we missed the first Bar.

00:06:05.620 --> 00:06:08.810
But I figured, just go ahead.

00:06:08.810 --> 00:06:10.480
Don't worry about.

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:13.230
But I also noticed-- and I don't
know if anybody else caught

00:06:13.230 --> 00:06:15.820
this-- but when Robin was
doing the first piece,

00:06:15.820 --> 00:06:19.230
he played one piece of
just kind of like delays,

00:06:19.230 --> 00:06:21.260
and just like a wah
wah on trombone.

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:23.120
And then he played
a second piece,

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:27.270
that was-- he started
with a drum pad,

00:06:27.270 --> 00:06:30.960
and started looping that, and
knowing some of those rhythms,

00:06:30.960 --> 00:06:36.090
I knew that if you don't get
the loop right in the drum--.

00:06:36.090 --> 00:06:39.010
You can record it with a kind
of a glitch, which he did.

00:06:39.010 --> 00:06:44.510
And he didn't
remember how to delete

00:06:44.510 --> 00:06:46.250
the last thing he recorded.

00:06:46.250 --> 00:06:49.550
So you just see, do I go
ahead with this thing,

00:06:49.550 --> 00:06:52.960
which is not really perfect?

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:54.910
And at one point
I could just see,

00:06:54.910 --> 00:06:56.870
like, he's just
going to go with it.

00:06:56.870 --> 00:06:58.700
And put the rest
of the stuff in,

00:06:58.700 --> 00:07:00.545
and start over
dubbing the trombone.

00:07:00.545 --> 00:07:03.590
And start playing on top of it.

00:07:03.590 --> 00:07:09.470
So I could look back and
think of a handful of things

00:07:09.470 --> 00:07:12.457
that, if this is a published
DVD, or published recording,

00:07:12.457 --> 00:07:14.290
you would hope you'd
be able to fix somehow.

00:07:14.290 --> 00:07:17.120
Or have another take
of, or whatever.

00:07:17.120 --> 00:07:19.896
But I think the wonderful
thing about a live performance

00:07:19.896 --> 00:07:25.730
is, it's like how do you get
out of the situation you're in?

00:07:25.730 --> 00:07:28.060
I've seen sax players,
and their neck strap

00:07:28.060 --> 00:07:30.810
breaks during a solo,
and they keep playing.

00:07:30.810 --> 00:07:33.500
Or the snare drum breaks
in the middle of a solo,

00:07:33.500 --> 00:07:36.352
and the drummer keeps playing.

00:07:36.352 --> 00:07:38.400
In a recording, you would stop.

00:07:38.400 --> 00:07:40.217
But in a performance,
it sort of like

00:07:40.217 --> 00:07:42.050
it was like a basketball
game, or something.

00:07:42.050 --> 00:07:43.980
You just can't say, I've
gotta go tie my shoe.

00:07:43.980 --> 00:07:45.310
Everybody wait.

00:07:45.310 --> 00:07:46.750
You just have to
do it, and that's

00:07:46.750 --> 00:07:52.225
a really fascinating kind of
challenge You had a question.

00:07:52.225 --> 00:07:55.250
AUDIENCE: What were you
doing in between solos,

00:07:55.250 --> 00:07:57.070
when you're going
up to your computer.

00:07:57.070 --> 00:07:59.361
Were you changing variables,
or just playing new loops?

00:08:01.215 --> 00:08:02.590
NEIL LEONARD:
Between the pieces?

00:08:02.590 --> 00:08:03.585
AUDIENCE: No.

00:08:03.585 --> 00:08:04.710
NEIL LEONARD: In the piece?

00:08:04.710 --> 00:08:05.293
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:08:07.579 --> 00:08:09.120
NEIL LEONARD: I'm
trying to remember.

00:08:09.120 --> 00:08:12.750
In the first piece I played--.

00:08:12.750 --> 00:08:14.705
Depends on the piece.

00:08:14.705 --> 00:08:18.030
Sometimes there is
a combination of-- I

00:08:18.030 --> 00:08:20.790
would like to be able to
do everything on the fly,

00:08:20.790 --> 00:08:25.485
and if I had four hands I
could do everything on the fly.

00:08:25.485 --> 00:08:27.050
So I could play the
saxophone, and I

00:08:27.050 --> 00:08:28.160
could be in front
of the computer,

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:29.618
and make the computer
do its thing.

00:08:29.618 --> 00:08:33.159
So mentally I think
I could do that, too.

00:08:33.159 --> 00:08:36.590
I could set it up so
more hands-on involvement

00:08:36.590 --> 00:08:38.090
with the computer
would be possible,

00:08:38.090 --> 00:08:39.214
but I could still play sax.

00:08:39.214 --> 00:08:41.340
But I only have two hands.

00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:45.700
And the sax is like the banjo.

00:08:48.970 --> 00:08:51.280
Your hands really
have to be there.

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:53.670
You can't really get them
off, and keep playing.

00:08:53.670 --> 00:08:56.730
You can't get both of
them off and keep playing.

00:08:56.730 --> 00:09:00.829
So some of the music
is created in advance.

00:09:00.829 --> 00:09:02.370
So the stuff, which
I think it played

00:09:02.370 --> 00:09:04.100
in class last week--
there's a piece I played

00:09:04.100 --> 00:09:05.933
that was like time
stretch voice and bells--

00:09:05.933 --> 00:09:07.020
we talked about that.

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:10.425
So that is really
kind of a module

00:09:10.425 --> 00:09:12.280
of a piece that's composed.

00:09:12.280 --> 00:09:14.067
So a lot of time,
it's like working

00:09:14.067 --> 00:09:15.150
in Photoshop or something.

00:09:15.150 --> 00:09:16.200
You sit there and you
work, and you work,

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:17.158
and you work in sounds.

00:09:17.158 --> 00:09:20.760
And you see if they
need any modifications.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:22.350
You see how to combine them.

00:09:22.350 --> 00:09:26.490
You kind of get a sense of the
dramatic flow of the piece.

00:09:26.490 --> 00:09:28.530
You work it out.

00:09:28.530 --> 00:09:31.040
And then you bring that
file to the concert.

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:33.050
And some of that's playback.

00:09:33.050 --> 00:09:35.390
So some of it's play back,
and some of it's live.

00:09:35.390 --> 00:09:38.800
Anything that sounded like
process saxophone was live.

00:09:38.800 --> 00:09:41.190
But if it sounds like
it was voice, then

00:09:41.190 --> 00:09:43.790
that was a vocalist who was
recorded, and then processed,

00:09:43.790 --> 00:09:45.830
and then kind of montaged.

00:09:45.830 --> 00:09:49.100
So sometimes it was like
triggering the next samples.

00:09:49.100 --> 00:09:51.910
I think in the last
piece I played,

00:09:51.910 --> 00:09:54.600
I made the software for
that just that week,

00:09:54.600 --> 00:09:55.970
if not a couple days before.

00:09:58.770 --> 00:10:01.920
That one I think I managed
to mostly do for the panel.

00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:03.637
But if it was
getting squirrelly,

00:10:03.637 --> 00:10:05.220
I may have gone to
the computer to try

00:10:05.220 --> 00:10:07.845
to get it to behave better.

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:13.070
So anything from just
triggering files,

00:10:13.070 --> 00:10:15.960
to kind of a small adjustments
to keep it all reined in.

00:10:18.880 --> 00:10:21.250
AUDIENCE: So when you
were playing the pieces,

00:10:21.250 --> 00:10:23.770
I actually thought that some
of the process saxophone

00:10:23.770 --> 00:10:24.850
was recorded.

00:10:24.850 --> 00:10:26.530
As I was watching
your foot and seen

00:10:26.530 --> 00:10:28.040
when you pressed the pedal.

00:10:28.040 --> 00:10:30.182
And it looked like the
pedal did lots of-- I

00:10:30.182 --> 00:10:32.140
initially expected the
pedal would be something

00:10:32.140 --> 00:10:33.725
simple, like the
pedal adds the delay.

00:10:33.725 --> 00:10:36.725
But the pedal caused so
many different effects

00:10:36.725 --> 00:10:38.855
that I assumed some of
the saxophone effects

00:10:38.855 --> 00:10:41.890
has been pre-recorded and the
pedal was playing them back.

00:10:41.890 --> 00:10:45.570
What exactly did you
program the pedal to do?

00:10:45.570 --> 00:10:48.300
NEIL LEONARD: The pedal just
sends a signal to the computer.

00:10:48.300 --> 00:10:50.720
So it's kind of like a mouse.

00:10:50.720 --> 00:10:54.560
It, by itself, is really simple.

00:10:54.560 --> 00:10:56.970
You can read the switches
from the computer.

00:10:56.970 --> 00:10:59.580
But the way the computer
is set up to respond,

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:03.250
the way I set it up in a concert
to respond to the footwork

00:11:03.250 --> 00:11:06.672
work, was fairly
straightforward.

00:11:06.672 --> 00:11:08.970
The computer does three
things to the sax.

00:11:11.900 --> 00:11:17.170
It will do different
kinds of delays.

00:11:17.170 --> 00:11:21.580
And the delays
will-- maybe when we

00:11:21.580 --> 00:11:23.450
get through, if you're
still interested,

00:11:23.450 --> 00:11:27.200
I could show how the
delay stuff works,

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:36.200
but-- the delay
business works two ways.

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:37.600
One is, it makes an echo.

00:11:37.600 --> 00:11:42.810
And the second thing it does, if
you think about the early tape

00:11:42.810 --> 00:11:49.014
delays, they have a tape
loop, that just rotated.

00:11:49.014 --> 00:11:50.680
The tape loop was
played, and then there

00:11:50.680 --> 00:11:52.920
were different playback
heads, to play it back

00:11:52.920 --> 00:11:54.370
at different points.

00:11:54.370 --> 00:11:56.850
So you have one record
head, and then you

00:11:56.850 --> 00:11:59.750
have multiple playback
heads that can be moved.

00:11:59.750 --> 00:12:02.060
And if you move,
they kind of echo.

00:12:02.060 --> 00:12:04.550
The ricochet kind of effect.

00:12:04.550 --> 00:12:18.400
The echo effect changes from
like [MIMING ECHO EFFECT]

00:12:18.400 --> 00:12:21.370
You can change those
echoes where there on time.

00:12:21.370 --> 00:12:26.390
If you move the
playback head, it's

00:12:26.390 --> 00:12:30.530
also a changing the speed
that its reading the tape.

00:12:30.530 --> 00:12:34.265
So if you have a note which
is [MAKES NOTE SOUND].

00:12:34.265 --> 00:12:35.960
And the tape is going like this.

00:12:35.960 --> 00:12:38.320
And you move the
playback head this way,

00:12:38.320 --> 00:12:41.890
you're going to get
glissando [MAKES NOTE SOUND]

00:12:41.890 --> 00:12:45.090
Because you're increasing the
speed at which the tape is

00:12:45.090 --> 00:12:46.690
passing over the playback head.

00:12:46.690 --> 00:12:48.860
If you move it the
other way, it goes down.

00:12:48.860 --> 00:12:51.900
So in the digital world,
you can get that, too.

00:12:51.900 --> 00:12:59.590
So, the delays are kind of
modeling a tape delay system.

00:12:59.590 --> 00:13:03.650
You can speed up, while you're
sort of moving the playback

00:13:03.650 --> 00:13:08.630
heads, you get
pitch consequences.

00:13:08.630 --> 00:13:12.295
Or kind of result in glassindos,
or glassindi, as well.

00:13:16.810 --> 00:13:18.490
The other, third
thing which makes

00:13:18.490 --> 00:13:20.410
the delay business
complicated, is there's

00:13:20.410 --> 00:13:24.350
a foot pedal which--
not everything's

00:13:24.350 --> 00:13:27.520
going to delay-- which
changes things radically.

00:13:27.520 --> 00:13:33.370
So if you play a phrase,
and at the end of the phrase

00:13:33.370 --> 00:13:38.050
you feed more of
that into the delay,

00:13:38.050 --> 00:13:39.790
it kind of accentuates
that one thing.

00:13:39.790 --> 00:13:42.720
Sort of like a sustained
pedal on a piano.

00:13:42.720 --> 00:13:44.470
If you put it down for
