00:51:59.880 --> 00:52:01.550
NEIL LEONARD: So you're
starting to use it now?

00:52:01.550 --> 00:52:01.880
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:52:01.880 --> 00:52:02.588
NEIL LEONARD: OK.

00:52:02.588 --> 00:52:03.214
Just curious.

00:52:03.214 --> 00:52:05.442
AUDIENCE: In the
past, though, I worked

00:52:05.442 --> 00:52:08.200
with Serato Scratch
Live, though.

00:52:08.200 --> 00:52:11.276
Actually, I use that for DJ'ing.

00:52:11.276 --> 00:52:12.160
NEIL LEONARD: OK.

00:52:12.160 --> 00:52:15.585
Yes, but in terms
of-- when I asked

00:52:15.585 --> 00:52:17.710
the question of how many
of you have done something

00:52:17.710 --> 00:52:23.405
like this live, what
I'm wondering about

00:52:23.405 --> 00:52:26.710
is how many people have
recorded sounds on their own,

00:52:26.710 --> 00:52:30.090
and used them in a
musical performance?

00:52:30.090 --> 00:52:32.799
You have?

00:52:32.799 --> 00:52:33.465
For composition.

00:52:33.465 --> 00:52:34.280
OK.

00:52:34.280 --> 00:52:35.550
And performance is a
little bit different,

00:52:35.550 --> 00:52:37.216
but it's a little bit
the same, as well.

00:52:42.280 --> 00:52:46.390
It is really interesting to
hear what you guys came up with,

00:52:46.390 --> 00:52:48.370
not knowing you very well.

00:52:48.370 --> 00:52:50.680
With my Berkeley
students, I always

00:52:50.680 --> 00:52:53.860
feel like, when they bring
in their assignments,

00:52:53.860 --> 00:52:55.159
it sounds so much like them.

00:52:55.159 --> 00:52:56.950
But I have a longer
time to work with them.

00:52:56.950 --> 00:53:02.150
So I can make some
more connections.

00:53:06.700 --> 00:53:11.220
One of the things that came
up in watching you perform,

00:53:11.220 --> 00:53:23.120
is where is the value
in doing something

00:53:23.120 --> 00:53:25.370
you haven't done before, or
something that you may not

00:53:25.370 --> 00:53:26.750
be comfortable with?

00:53:26.750 --> 00:53:31.590
As a sort of
experimental adventure.

00:53:31.590 --> 00:53:37.800
And when I listen to Sarah,
and Ben's and James's piece,

00:53:37.800 --> 00:53:42.790
one of the things which
seems to be interesting,

00:53:42.790 --> 00:53:46.321
is that you guys didn't really
know where it was going to go.

00:53:46.321 --> 00:53:48.070
You didn't know where
it was going to end.

00:53:48.070 --> 00:53:50.970
You said, that's not
quite what we rehearsed.

00:53:50.970 --> 00:53:54.300
And that can be a
really wonderful thing.

00:53:54.300 --> 00:53:59.070
Because the opposite is-- when
I played the concert that you

00:53:59.070 --> 00:54:01.430
saw, if it happened
exactly the way

00:54:01.430 --> 00:54:10.270
it happened a time before,
or happened every time,

00:54:10.270 --> 00:54:13.560
you run the risk
of the spark dying.

00:54:13.560 --> 00:54:16.380
So the excitement of
the performance-- kind

00:54:16.380 --> 00:54:17.980
of like rigor mortis sets in.

00:54:17.980 --> 00:54:21.470
The spontaneity goes
away, and the spark.

00:54:21.470 --> 00:54:24.440
The excitement for
the performer can

00:54:24.440 --> 00:54:25.730
be linked to the spontaneity.

00:54:25.730 --> 00:54:28.345
And you lose the excitement
for the performer,

00:54:28.345 --> 00:54:29.410
and the spontaneity.

00:54:29.410 --> 00:54:30.910
So when you guys
were playing didn't

00:54:30.910 --> 00:54:34.410
know where it was going
to go, I thought, well,

00:54:34.410 --> 00:54:38.250
that's actually a good
thing to just bring up.

00:54:38.250 --> 00:54:39.905
Because that's the
desired effect.

00:54:39.905 --> 00:54:42.380
And it's a struggle
for the improviser, who

00:54:42.380 --> 00:54:47.020
plays for decades, to keep
the thing feeling fresh.

00:54:47.020 --> 00:54:52.980
I know for me, there
are things you can do.

00:54:52.980 --> 00:54:54.695
I guess it's like when
you're performing,

00:54:54.695 --> 00:54:57.650
and you're distracted, or
you're just not really--.

00:55:00.440 --> 00:55:02.510
What I'm getting at is,
for me the performances

00:55:02.510 --> 00:55:07.630
are the least satisfying when
one of two thing happens.

00:55:07.630 --> 00:55:12.060
Either I can't relax,
and get in the play.

00:55:12.060 --> 00:55:15.820
So if it's a concert,
like with Robin,

00:55:15.820 --> 00:55:19.550
for example, if I feel for
any reason uncomfortable,

00:55:19.550 --> 00:55:22.090
if the challenge of it
kinda psych's me out,

00:55:22.090 --> 00:55:25.392
or I don't think I know
the music well enough,

00:55:25.392 --> 00:55:27.225
and I start to play,
and all of a sudden you

00:55:27.225 --> 00:55:31.670
feel that tension, that anxiety
of trying to get to the music.

00:55:31.670 --> 00:55:34.450
It's not like a stage fright,
it's not like a performance

00:55:34.450 --> 00:55:37.182
anxiety, but you feel
like you're forcing it.

00:55:37.182 --> 00:55:38.890
And once you feel like
you're forcing it,

00:55:38.890 --> 00:55:42.100
in a performance of
improvised music,

00:55:42.100 --> 00:55:45.600
you begin to lose a
little bit of control.

00:55:45.600 --> 00:55:48.200
And then the other
thing is if I feel like,

00:55:48.200 --> 00:55:50.180
oh I just played what
I played yesterday.

00:55:50.180 --> 00:55:53.380
I did what I knew
I could do easily.

00:55:53.380 --> 00:55:56.220
Then you don't
discover anything new.

00:55:56.220 --> 00:55:59.420
And I think that what's kind
of fundamental in improvisation

00:55:59.420 --> 00:56:02.450
is this feeling that you're
discovering something new.

00:56:02.450 --> 00:56:04.390
Even if small things
are new, but you

00:56:04.390 --> 00:56:08.905
keeping that little bit
of the activity alive.

00:56:17.020 --> 00:56:19.460
Doing something which is
not necessarily comfortable

00:56:19.460 --> 00:56:24.230
or not something
you've done before

00:56:24.230 --> 00:56:28.020
can sometimes turn
into a big gain.

00:56:28.020 --> 00:56:31.240
The other things I was
thinking about with that piece

00:56:31.240 --> 00:56:35.760
are-- At first I was
thinking I wanted everybody

00:56:35.760 --> 00:56:36.980
to record yourself.

00:56:36.980 --> 00:56:51.520
And then you guys,
Sarah, James, and Ben,

00:56:51.520 --> 00:56:54.529
at first I was a
little bit concerned,

00:56:54.529 --> 00:56:57.070
because you just grabbed some
sounds from the computer, which

00:56:57.070 --> 00:56:59.050
I told you not to do.

00:56:59.050 --> 00:57:01.120
But the thing which I
thought worked really well

00:57:01.120 --> 00:57:05.470
is, we have such a visceral
connection to those sounds.

00:57:05.470 --> 00:57:09.350
They have a tremendous
meaning for us.

00:57:09.350 --> 00:57:12.350
They give us knee
jerk responses,

00:57:12.350 --> 00:57:16.300
Like if my cell phone is
in inadvertently right now.

00:57:16.300 --> 00:57:20.270
And I hear a text message sound,
all of a sudden I kind of jump.

00:57:20.270 --> 00:57:23.680
My body reacts like I
have to do something.

00:57:23.680 --> 00:57:27.490
So those sounds have a
tremendous kind of power.

00:57:27.490 --> 00:57:31.050
And we have very
important associations,

00:57:31.050 --> 00:57:32.920
strong associations,
with those sounds.

00:57:32.920 --> 00:57:35.419
So they're totally loaded, and
the way you played with them,

00:57:35.419 --> 00:57:37.362
I thought was
really, really fun.

00:57:37.362 --> 00:57:39.420
I think that the
Windows operating system

00:57:39.420 --> 00:57:42.770
is more musical than the Mac.

00:57:42.770 --> 00:57:43.280
Side note.

00:57:50.880 --> 00:57:52.690
I'm just putting out
some ideas that I

00:57:52.690 --> 00:57:54.880
was thinking about
listening to everybody play.

00:57:54.880 --> 00:57:56.320
The other thing
I was thinking of

00:57:56.320 --> 00:58:01.980
is-- and this is also very
true in Austin's piece--

00:58:01.980 --> 00:58:05.157
is that working with computers.

00:58:05.157 --> 00:58:06.740
Computers are not
nearly as responsive

00:58:06.740 --> 00:58:09.870
as a flute, a
violin, as a trumpet.

00:58:09.870 --> 00:58:12.510
You're making music
with your index finger.

00:58:12.510 --> 00:58:15.190
You're not using your whole arm.

00:58:15.190 --> 00:58:16.850
You're not using your mouth.

00:58:16.850 --> 00:58:19.730
You're not using your breathing.

00:58:19.730 --> 00:58:21.440
You're not even
using your hands.

00:58:21.440 --> 00:58:23.560
Are using your index finger.

00:58:23.560 --> 00:58:24.800
You're moving and clicking.

00:58:29.110 --> 00:58:32.510
But I'm also in my
own work, interested

00:58:32.510 --> 00:58:35.920
in the resistance
of the materials.

00:58:35.920 --> 00:58:39.380
So, the computer
is totally limited.

00:58:39.380 --> 00:58:40.647
Or this assignment I gave you.

00:58:40.647 --> 00:58:42.980
Make a performance, it's going
to be three minutes long.

00:58:42.980 --> 00:58:44.313
You only have a week to make it.

00:58:44.313 --> 00:58:46.440
You're going to record
sounds in your own.

00:58:46.440 --> 00:58:50.210
Right there it limits what
you can do quite a bit.

00:58:50.210 --> 00:58:55.120
But when an artist is
presented with limitations,

00:58:55.120 --> 00:58:57.590
it's amazing to see what
artists come up with.

00:58:57.590 --> 00:58:59.430
So the resistance
of the materials

00:58:59.430 --> 00:59:01.060
takes you someplace new.

00:59:01.060 --> 00:59:04.344
So for example, I'm
reviewing a piece of music

00:59:04.344 --> 00:59:06.010
which is very difficult
to improvise on.

00:59:06.010 --> 00:59:08.630
A very complicated
set of chord changes.

00:59:08.630 --> 00:59:09.710
I tried the other day.

00:59:09.710 --> 00:59:12.240
I'm just going to play
with my left hand.

00:59:12.240 --> 00:59:14.790
The metronome was fast,
the harmonic progressions

00:59:14.790 --> 00:59:15.552
really hard.

00:59:15.552 --> 00:59:17.510
I'm playing the same
thing over and over again.

00:59:17.510 --> 00:59:19.670
I'm finding my rut.

00:59:19.670 --> 00:59:21.753
So what if I just play
with my left hand?

00:59:21.753 --> 00:59:23.350
And I tried that for while.

00:59:23.350 --> 00:59:25.290
And all of a sudden, I felt
like I'm getting out of my rut,

00:59:25.290 --> 00:59:27.123
because I had to think
about it differently.

00:59:27.123 --> 00:59:29.970
I had to find new things
that I could do this hand.

00:59:29.970 --> 00:59:31.890
Put them both back
into play again,

00:59:31.890 --> 00:59:33.520
and it feels like it's fresh.

00:59:33.520 --> 00:59:40.000
So the idea of doing this
very short exercise that

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:47.110
uses this kind of rigid,
somewhat unresponsive tool,

00:59:47.110 --> 00:59:51.340
to make music, has
historically produced

00:59:51.340 --> 00:59:55.170
some really interesting
things that we haven't got out

00:59:55.170 --> 00:59:58.795
of the previous
concert music practice.

01:00:02.090 --> 01:00:05.450
So those are just some of
things I was thinking about.

01:00:09.700 --> 01:00:11.680
I think if we were
to do this again--

01:00:11.680 --> 01:00:16.420
if this was a four unit
class, of if this was Berkeley

01:00:16.420 --> 01:00:22.860
and you were doing this
as your thesis project--

01:00:22.860 --> 01:00:27.050
I think the kind of challenges
I found in the last two pieces

01:00:27.050 --> 01:00:30.060
would be very interesting
to continue to explore.

01:00:30.060 --> 01:00:33.010
So what about when you've
overextended yourself.

01:00:33.010 --> 01:00:38.360
And you're playing some
piano, and some violin,

01:00:38.360 --> 01:00:39.600
and some computer.

01:00:39.600 --> 01:00:42.890
Or in my case-- you heard
me in Killian hall--

01:00:42.890 --> 01:00:45.232
I'm doing delay effects, and
I'm playing back samples,

01:00:45.232 --> 01:00:46.315
and I'm playing saxophone.

01:00:46.315 --> 01:00:49.710
And I'm beginning to
overextend myself.

01:00:49.710 --> 01:00:53.430
It's an interesting
problem, and the solutions

01:00:53.430 --> 01:00:55.622
you found-- it was wonderful
to watch you trying

01:00:55.622 --> 01:00:57.330
to grapple with that
problem, and come up

01:00:57.330 --> 01:00:59.850
with some very
interesting solutions.

01:00:59.850 --> 01:01:04.630
And I am also very
keen on this idea of,

01:01:04.630 --> 01:01:06.750
is there a set of
sounds that you

01:01:06.750 --> 01:01:09.995
can find that have a
really special quality?

01:01:17.280 --> 01:01:20.210
When you hear Glenn Gould
play the Goldberg variations

01:01:20.210 --> 01:01:23.380
on piano-- and the aria
of the Goldberg variations

01:01:23.380 --> 01:01:28.970
is a very, very simple piece--
and he just sounds phenomenal.

01:01:28.970 --> 01:01:30.170
He's playing quarter notes.

01:01:30.170 --> 01:01:33.102
It's just mind boggling
good, and he has barely

01:01:33.102 --> 01:01:34.060
even started the piece.

01:01:34.060 --> 01:01:35.520
This is amazing.

01:01:35.520 --> 01:01:36.760
It's the way he plays.

01:01:36.760 --> 01:01:40.000
But I guess that's the next
question I have for you guys.

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:41.570
Are there particular
sounds that you

01:01:41.570 --> 01:01:45.700
hear that would be a
good start to a piece?

01:01:45.700 --> 01:01:49.420
That just have that kind
of mesmerizing effect.

01:01:49.420 --> 01:01:51.170
And they're not
necessarily music.

01:01:51.170 --> 01:01:53.270
I think with the Windows
operating system piece,

01:01:53.270 --> 01:01:56.350
you also had the
advantage of some

01:01:56.350 --> 01:01:59.610
of those micro compositions.

01:01:59.610 --> 01:02:00.922
Like [MAKES NOTE SOUNDS].

01:02:00.922 --> 01:02:01.630
Whatever that is.

01:02:01.630 --> 01:02:04.260
That's like the shut down
sound, or the boot up sound,

01:02:04.260 --> 01:02:05.106
or something.

01:02:05.106 --> 01:02:07.230
Like there are already kind
of audio jingles, which

01:02:07.230 --> 01:02:10.147
have been very, very
carefully created.

01:02:10.147 --> 01:02:11.480
And we've heard them many times.

01:02:11.480 --> 01:02:13.200
They have tremendous
meaning for us.

01:02:13.200 --> 01:02:17.060
But are there sounds that you
hear in the world around you,

01:02:17.060 --> 01:02:19.390
that would make a really
good beginning of a piece.

01:02:19.390 --> 01:02:20.790
Let's just forget the
whole piece for now.

01:02:20.790 --> 01:02:22.540
Let's just say the
beginning of the piece.

01:02:22.540 --> 01:02:24.248
Something that would
be fantastic to hear

01:02:24.248 --> 01:02:24.980
at the beginning.

01:02:24.980 --> 01:02:26.855
That would be an
interesting thing to pursue.

01:02:32.870 --> 01:02:37.620
I'm trying to remember the
other solo artist in this group.

01:02:37.620 --> 01:02:38.800
Jacob, right?

01:02:38.800 --> 01:02:46.425
Jacob, where I would like
to see that work go is,

01:02:46.425 --> 01:02:49.000
is there a way that you
can share the improvisation

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:49.750
with the computer?

01:02:49.750 --> 01:02:53.990
So you created a
piece of software

01:02:53.990 --> 01:02:57.990
that basically automates an
idea about improvisation.

01:02:57.990 --> 01:03:01.326
You have an idea of how
the sounds could play.

01:03:01.326 --> 01:03:02.950
Sometimes they play
together, Sometimes

01:03:02.950 --> 01:03:03.870
there's silence between them.

01:03:03.870 --> 01:03:05.050
Sometimes there's 3 over 1.

01:03:05.050 --> 01:03:07.150
Sometimes they're dove
tailing were overlapping.

01:03:07.150 --> 01:03:09.380
Sometimes they're not.

01:03:09.380 --> 01:03:12.660
Is there a way to
extend that so you

01:03:12.660 --> 01:03:15.950
are a physical participant
in the improvisation,

01:03:15.950 --> 01:03:19.849
and the computer is
playing a disembodied you.

01:03:19.849 --> 01:03:21.390
Because basically
what it's doing now

01:03:21.390 --> 01:03:22.473
is like a disembodied you.

01:03:22.473 --> 01:03:27.850
It's your idea implemented
as a program that

01:03:27.850 --> 01:03:30.640
will execute your idea.

01:03:30.640 --> 01:03:32.940
Is there a way to
have two of you?

01:03:32.940 --> 01:03:37.970
The virtual you, which is what
we heard, and the you present.

01:03:37.970 --> 01:03:40.380
So, I'm a teacher, so
I'm always thinking

01:03:40.380 --> 01:03:42.360
for my own students,
what do I do

01:03:42.360 --> 01:03:44.730
to get everybody
to the next step?

01:03:44.730 --> 01:03:45.950
Because we're never done.

01:03:45.950 --> 01:03:47.220
I study all the time.

01:03:47.220 --> 01:03:48.270
I try to learn new stuff.

01:03:48.270 --> 01:03:48.340
I could tell you all about that.

01:03:48.340 --> 01:03:50.140
We don't have the time.

01:03:50.140 --> 01:03:53.920
But I'm always thinking for
you guys, what's the next step?

01:03:53.920 --> 01:03:55.920
And I think that
for Jacob's work,

01:03:55.920 --> 01:03:57.090
that would be a next step.

01:04:01.420 --> 01:04:03.290
I'll just try to
touch on one more.

01:04:03.290 --> 01:04:05.765
Alex, Chelsea, and Chris's,
the homework theme.

01:04:10.710 --> 01:04:15.470
I guess, if you hadn't
told me it was homework.

01:04:15.470 --> 01:04:18.470
I might have been able to
distinguish it from the others.

01:04:18.470 --> 01:04:20.770
But I love the idea of homework.

01:04:20.770 --> 01:04:24.410
And what moment
of homework would

01:04:24.410 --> 01:04:26.280
be really great to zero in on.

01:04:26.280 --> 01:04:27.170
It's so rich.

01:04:27.170 --> 01:04:29.790
Is it like procrastination?

01:04:29.790 --> 01:04:34.500
The feeling that you
learned something new?

01:04:34.500 --> 01:04:37.669
The anxiety of, oh, no
I've got Neil's assignment,

01:04:37.669 --> 01:04:39.460
it's due in and hour
and I haven't started.

01:04:39.460 --> 01:04:44.240
There's all kinds of ways
to think about homework.

01:04:44.240 --> 01:04:48.880
And it's such a central
part of your lives.

01:04:48.880 --> 01:04:52.160
What could you do to
take that another step?

01:04:52.160 --> 01:04:54.400
I think it's a great theme.

01:04:54.400 --> 01:04:56.120
And what could you
do to distinguish it

01:04:56.120 --> 01:04:58.320
from all the other
works we heard?

01:04:58.320 --> 01:05:00.940
So I think that, in short,
all these pieces are really

01:05:00.940 --> 01:05:02.510
wonderful beginnings.

01:05:02.510 --> 01:05:10.210
And I don't think any
of these beginnings

01:05:10.210 --> 01:05:12.730
is more or less
valuable than any other.

01:05:12.730 --> 01:05:15.900
But I guess my bias
is thinking, if we

01:05:15.900 --> 01:05:19.150
were to continue this,
what would be a next step

01:05:19.150 --> 01:05:21.950
to engage in.

01:05:21.950 --> 01:05:26.899
To take the same ideas and
develop them a little bit more?

01:05:26.899 --> 01:05:28.440
MARK HARVEY: Great
thank you so much.

